Detailed content

1. Definition and formal expression
- Hamming distance between two equal-length sequences x and y of length n is H(x,y) = sum_{i=0..n-1} [x_i != y_i], i.e., the count of positions at which corresponding symbols differ.
- For binary strings (bit vectors) a and b the Hamming distance equals the population count (number of 1 bits) of a XOR b.
- Properties: metric (non-negativity, identity of indiscernibles, symmetry, triangle inequality). Time complexity for direct per-position comparison is O(n).

2. Integer/binary Hamming distance (XOR + popcount)
- Compute v = x XOR y (bitwise exclusive-or). The Hamming distance is popcount(v), where popcount counts set bits (1s) in v.
- Popcount via Kernighan's method (loop that clears lowest set bit):
  - Initialize count = 0
  - While v != 0: v = v & (v - 1); count = count + 1
  - Return count
- Complexity: loop runs once per set bit in v; worst-case O(b) where b = number of bits in representation; average proportional to Hamming distance.
- Where available, use hardware/popcount intrinsic (e.g., GCC __builtin_popcount / __builtin_popcountll) for constant-time popcount using processor instruction.

3. Algorithms and complexity
- Per-position string comparison: O(n) time, O(1) extra space.
- Integer XOR + Kernighan: time O(h) where h is number of differing bits, worst-case O(b).
- Use fixed-width integer operations where available for predictable cost; for very large integers use big-integer libraries or BigInt and a loop/pairwise chunking approach.

4. String Hamming distance: code unit vs code point vs grapheme
- UTF-16 representation: JavaScript strings are sequences of UTF-16 code units. length and index-based access operate on UTF-16 code units, not Unicode code points or grapheme clusters.
- charAt(index) returns exactly one UTF-16 code unit (a string of length 1) or empty string if index out-of-range. It may return a lone surrogate if used inside a surrogate pair.
- codePointAt(pos) reads a whole Unicode code point starting at pos (surrogate-aware) and returns the numeric code point value.
- Iterator / spread operator / for...of iterate by Unicode code points: [...str] or for (const ch of str) yields code-point-aware tokens.
- Grapheme clusters (user-perceived characters) may combine multiple code points (combining marks, emoji ZWJ sequences). Iteration by grapheme clusters requires specialized handling (Intl.Segmenter or external libraries). JavaScript built-ins do not split grapheme clusters automatically.
- For string Hamming distance, decide the unit explicitly:
  - unit = 'codeUnit': compare charAt(i) for i in 0..n-1 (fast; n = str.length)
  - unit = 'codePoint': compare arrays from [...str] or Array.from(str) and require equal codePoint counts
  - unit = 'grapheme': use Intl.Segmenter (if available) or grapheme-splitter library; equal cluster counts required
- If strings have unequal lengths in the chosen unit, Hamming distance is undefined; either reject or normalize (pad/truncate) per application rules.

5. JavaScript APIs relevant to implementation (signatures and exact behavior)
- String.prototype.charAt(index)
  - Signature: charAt(index?: number) -> string
  - Parameter: index converted to integer, undefined -> 0
  - Return: a string containing exactly one UTF-16 code unit; returns empty string when index out of range.
  - Notes: may return lone surrogates; not surrogate-pair-aware.

- String.prototype.codePointAt(pos)
  - Signature: codePointAt(pos: number) -> number | undefined
  - Returns numeric Unicode code point starting at position pos (surrogate-pair-aware). Returns undefined if pos out of range.

- String.prototype.normalize()
  - Signature: normalize(form?: string) -> string
  - Behavior: canonical Unicode normalization (NFC/NFD/NFKC/NFKD) used to make visually equivalent sequences comparable.

- String iteration (Symbol.iterator) and spread
  - [...str] or for (const ch of str) iterate by Unicode code points (surrogate-aware). Use when unit == 'codePoint'.

- Number.prototype.toString(radix?)
  - Signature: toString(radix?: number) -> string
  - Parameter: radix integer in 2..36; default 10; throws RangeError if radix <2 or >36.
  - Behavior: returns textual representation in given base; negative numbers return '-' + positive representation, not two's complement.
  - Use: (n).toString(2) to get binary string for n (beware Number size/precision limits).

- BigInt and large integers
  - For integers larger than Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER prefer BigInt; use BigInt literals or BigInt() and implement popcount on BigInt with repeated & and >> operations, or split into 32/64-bit chunks.

6. Edge cases and pitfalls
- Mismatched lengths: Hamming distance is defined only for equal-length sequences. On unequal lengths either throw an error or define a padding policy (explicitly state it).
- UTF-16 surrogate pairs: charAt and length operate on code units; to compare user-perceived characters use code point iteration or grapheme segmentation.
- Unicode normalization: visually identical strings may have different code point sequences (composed vs decomposed). Use str.normalize('NFC') (or chosen form) before comparison when normalization is required.
- Numeric limits in JS: Number is an IEEE-754 double; bitwise operators coerce to 32-bit signed ints before operation. For >32-bit Hamming computations, use BigInt or string-based binary conversions.
- Negative numbers: Number.toString(2) for negatives yields a prefixed '-' followed by the positive binary digits; do not treat that as two's complement unless explicitly converting to fixed-width two's complement representation.
- Performance: converting large numeric ranges to binary strings and iterating characters is slower than XOR+popcount on native integers; prefer bitwise Kernighan/popcount when possible.

7. Implementation patterns (explicit, executable algorithm descriptions)

A. Integer Hamming distance using XOR + Kernighan (language-agnostic pattern)
- Inputs: x, y integers of the same fixed width (or treated as bit vectors).
- Steps:
  1. v = x XOR y
  2. count = 0
  3. while v != 0:
     v = v & (v - 1)   # clears lowest-order 1 bit
     count = count + 1
  4. return count
- Complexity: O(popcount(v)); recommended where native integer XOR and bitwise are available.

B. JavaScript integer Hamming distance (32-bit, using bitwise ops)
- Signature: function hammingDistance32(x: number, y: number): number
- Steps:
  1. const v = (x ^ y) >>> 0    // ensure unsigned 32-bit
  2. let count = 0
  3. let n = v
  4. while (n !== 0) { n &= (n - 1); count++; }
  5. return count
- Notes: bitwise operations coerce to 32-bit signed integers; use >>> 0 to treat as unsigned where needed.
- For numbers outside 32-bit range, convert to BigInt or to binary string safely using BigInt.

C. JavaScript BigInt Hamming distance (arbitrary precision)
- Signature: function hammingDistanceBigInt(a: bigint, b: bigint): number
- Steps:
  1. let v = a ^ b  // BigInt XOR supported
  2. let count = 0n
  3. while (v !== 0n) { v &= (v - 1n); count++; }
  4. return Number(count)
- Notes: convert to Number only if count fits in Number range or return bigint count.

D. String Hamming distance (code-point aware)
- Signature: function hammingDistanceStrings(a: string, b: string, unit = 'codePoint') -> number
- Steps (unit == 'codePoint'):
  1. const A = [...a]; const B = [...b]; // spread operator produces array of code points
  2. if (A.length !== B.length) throw Error('Strings must have equal code-point length')
  3. let count = 0
  4. for (let i = 0; i < A.length; i++) { if (A[i] !== B[i]) count++ }
  5. return count
- Steps (unit == 'codeUnit'):
  1. if (a.length !== b.length) throw Error('Strings must have equal code-unit length')
  2. let count = 0
  3. for (let i = 0; i < a.length; i++) { if (a.charAt(i) !== b.charAt(i)) count++ }
  4. return count
- Steps (unit == 'grapheme'):
  1. Use Intl.Segmenter if available: const seg = new Intl.Segmenter(locale, {granularity:'grapheme'})
  2. const A = Array.from(seg.segment(a), s => s.segment)
  3. const B = Array.from(seg.segment(b), s => s.segment)
  4. compare as above (length equality required)

E. Converting numbers to equal-length binary strings (if required for textual comparison)
- Steps:
  1. const binA = (a >>> 0).toString(2)  // or BigInt approach for large ints
  2. const binB = (b >>> 0).toString(2)
  3. const L = Math.max(binA.length, binB.length)
  4. const A = binA.padStart(L, '0'); const B = binB.padStart(L, '0')
  5. count differing chars in A and B
- Notes: padStart is available on String.prototype; beware sign handling and bit-width choices.

8. Best practices and troubleshooting
- Prefer native XOR + popcount intrinsics where available; they are fastest and constant-time in many architectures.
- In JavaScript, for integers within 32-bit range prefer bitwise XOR and Kernighan; for larger integers use BigInt and BigInt bitwise operators.
- Always decide and document the "unit" (codeUnit, codePoint, grapheme) before computing string Hamming distance; mismatched choices lead to subtle differences.
- When comparing user-visible characters, use normalization: a.normalize('NFC') to canonicalize composed/decomposed sequences.
- For grapheme clusters prefer Intl.Segmenter or a well-tested library; manual code-point iteration will split combined glyphs and produce incorrect distances.
- Troubleshooting steps when results differ from expectation:
  1. Verify the chosen unit and that both inputs have equal length in that unit.
  2. If using strings with accented characters, ensure both strings are normalized to the same Unicode normalization form.
  3. If using numeric conversions, check numeric ranges and whether bitwise coercions truncated values to 32-bit.
  4. Log intermediate values: XOR result (for binary), arrays used for string comparison, and lengths.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Time/space
  - Typical per-position string comparison: O(n) time, O(1) extra space (besides input arrays when using [...str]).
  - Integer Kernighan method: O(h) time where h = popcount(x ^ y), O(1) space.
- Numeric representation caveats (JS-specific)
  - Number uses IEEE-754 double-precision; bitwise ops coerce to 32-bit signed ints before operation. For fidelity beyond 32 bits, use BigInt.
- Unicode
  - Surrogate pair ranges: high surrogates 0xD800..0xDBFF, low surrogates 0xDC00..0xDFFF. Lone surrogates may appear if strings are not well-formed.
  - Normalization forms: NFC, NFD, NFKC, NFKD. Use str.normalize(form) to canonicalize.

REFERENCE DETAILS (API signatures, exact behaviors, patterns)
- String.prototype.charAt(index?: number) -> string
  - index coerced to integer; returns exactly one UTF-16 code unit string or '' if out of range.
- String.prototype.codePointAt(pos: number) -> number | undefined
  - Returns Unicode code point value starting at pos, surrogate-aware; undefined if pos out of range.
- String.prototype.normalize(form?: 'NFC'|'NFD'|'NFKC'|'NFKD') -> string
  - Returns normalized string; default form depends on implementation but specify explicit form for deterministic behavior.
- String iteration
  - for (const ch of str) and [...str] iterate code points (surrogate-aware), not grapheme clusters.
- Number.prototype.toString(radix?: number) -> string
  - radix integer 2..36; RangeError if out of range; negative numbers return '-' + positive representation; 0 and -0 return "0"; Infinity => "Infinity"; NaN => "NaN".
- Kernighan popcount pattern (integer)
  - while (v !== 0) { v &= (v - 1); count++; }
- JS 32-bit safe integer Hamming distance pattern
  - const v = (x ^ y) >>> 0; let n = v; while (n) { n &= (n - 1); count++; }
- BigInt Hamming pattern
  - Use BigInt XOR and BigInt arithmetic: while (v !== 0n) { v &= (v - 1n); count++; }

